@node MAINMENU "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu"
@prev MAIN


  After the double click on the icon you should see a small panel on the
  bottom of your screen with this buttons:


          @{"  ABOUT  " link ABOUT}   @{"  BACKUP  " link BACKUP}   @{" RESTORE " link RESTORE}   @{"   QUIT   " link QUIT}


  I hope the program works without errors. I'm not responsable for any lost
  data because of my program. For programmers who wants to know how the
  files are saved please also read the @{"technical part" link TECHNICAL}.


@endnode
@node TECHNICAL "Power Backup 1.01 »» Technical Informations"
@prev MAIN

  This section is only for programmers, especially for AMOS programmers.
  But if you're interested in how I store your data, just in case you
  must recover them yourself, read on.

  »» As you noticed all datas are saved into files of about 208K.
     This is because single files waste disc space and one large file
     decreases file access when restoring the files.

  »» Now the structure of the data. Remember that the data are splitted
     into 208K pieces:

     At the beginning you have this data:   HHHHHHHH----====

       HHHHHHHH ... is the identifiaction string "PPBACK10"
       ---- ....... longword with the number of files xor 0xA45B918D
       ==== ....... longword with the number of files xor 0xC2370E6F

     Then follows this data for each file:  IIII----DDDD====

       IIII ... longword information header identification: 0x2BAD4815
       ---- ... information data: SSSSTTTTUUUUVVVVWWWWXXXXYYZZ________
                 SSSS ... longword with original size
                 TTTT ... longword checksum of original data
                 UUUU ... longword with compressed size
                 VVVV ... longword checksum of compressed data
                 WWWW ... longword with date of the file
                 XXXX ... longword with time of the file
                 YY   ... word with protection flags
                 ZZ   ... word with length of complete file name
                 ____ ... string with complete path and file name
       DDDD ... longword information header identification: 0xE0F63C97
       ==== ... the compressed or original file data

  »» You need much fast memory if you want to backup large files. That's
     because I must load the file first and then try to compress it.
     I could split all files into 64K pieces, but that's much  more to
     do for me and I have no time now. Maybe I'll add this later.

  »» And finally some comments about the source. You need AMOS Pro and
     the AMCAF extension. The most interesting things are the interface
     programs and the directroy tree.

     *) Load the program data and run the resource bank editor. Go to
        the dialog programs and have a look on them. I hope it helps
        you how to use this powerful feature of AMOS Pro.

     *) More interesting is how I create the directroy tree. I'm
        allocating memory with the "AllocMem"-Systemcall dynamically!
        Read the comments carefully to understand how I build the tree.
        If you want to use it just grab all the procedures.

  Alright. Please test the program and contact @{"me" link INFO} if you find a new bug.

@endnode
@node ABOUT "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» About"
@prev MAINMENU

  You will see a quick information scrolling through the box with the
  power backup image. Click any key or mouse button to contine scrolling
  until the image reappears.

@endnode
@node BACKUP "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» Backup"
@prev MAINMENU

  This is the first option you may use. With it you save your data from
  your hard disc. Only follow the screen dialogs.

   @{HI "Selection Dialog"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  »» Root: Here you enter the root directory you want to start file
       selection. The reading of the directory tree is much faster if
       you enter 'Dh1:Pictures' instead of 'Dh1:' if you just want to
       backup your pictures there.

  »» Label: Here you enter a name for the backup discs. This is
       important for you to know which data you stored on a disc and
       also important for the restoring operation. NEVER relabel a
       backup disc yourself! Just if you don't need it anymore. You
       can @{"redirect" link REDIRECT} the backup to your hard disc here.

  »» The directory tree on the left: Click with left mouse button to
       select all files for a directory with all sub directories. Click
       with right mouse button to see all files of that directory in
       the file list at the right side. You can also use cursor up/down
       to scroll.

  »» The file list on the right: Here you see all files of the active
       directory. This is shown with a red background it the directory
       tree at the left side. Click with left mouse button to select
       a single file. You can also use cursor left/right to scroll.

  »» Add program files on first disc: This option adds the program, its
       data and the powerpacker.library onto the first disc and uses
       about 166K more disc space. Don't forget to make the first disc
       bootable! I think this option is very useful, especially if you
       backup your boot partition!

  »» Informations: Under the two selection boxes you see informations
       about the current root directory: amount of directories, number
       of files, size of all files in bytes and size of the selected
       files in bytes.

  »» Compression: Here you can change the compression effeciency. But
       you need the powerpacker.library if you compress your data. Next
       to it you see an approximation of discs you will need. Please
       read @{"here" link COMPRESSION} for a detailed description. Use may use the 'c' key
       to change compression efficiency.

  »» Okay/Cancel: Hmmm, well, click 'Okay' or the <Return> key to start
       the backup, or click 'Cancel' or the <ESC> key to abort.

   @{HI "Redirection Options"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  Optionally, if you @{"redirect" link REDIRECT} the backup to your hard disc, you'll see
  this dialog. Here you can choose between DD or HD floppies, and OS1.2+
  or OS2.0+ compatible splitting size. For OS1.2+ you have the OFS with
  488 bytes per block, OS2.0+ uses FFS and offers 512 bytes per block.
  That's a difference of about 40K for DD discs, and 80K for HD discs!

  Additionally you can leave some free space on the first disc. Type in
  the required amount in kilobytes, but you are limited to the half of
  the available disc size, depending on the settings above.

  Finally click 'Okay' to continue with the backup, or 'Cancel' to abort
  and return to the main menu.

   @{HI "File Backup Dialog"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  Now the backup starts. At the top you see a history list about all
  actions. In the middle you see the actions of the current file and at
  the bottom you see two progress panels, one for the number of files
  already saved, and one for how many disc space has been used.

  If you redirect the backup to your hard disc you can leave your AMIGA
  alone and can watch TV or meet your friends. (Hey, cool, isn't it?)
  Otherwise you may stay near your AMIGA and change discs.
  IMPORTANT: You can't break the backup now. Just the hard way! :-S

   @{HI "Final Backup Report"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  If all selected files have been saved you see a final report with some
  statistics. Click 'Save' if you want to save the history list. Else
  click 'Okay' to return to the main menu. If you redirected the backup
  you should copy the data from you hard disc to floppies. And after
  that test the backup with the @{"restore" link RESTORE} menu.

@endnode
@node RESTORE "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» Restore"
@prev MAINMENU

  Here you save your data back to your hard disc. You can also test your
  backup discs here before your store them in a secure place. Here we go:

   @{HI "Restore Options"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  »» Simulate: Activate this options if you don't really want to write
       your data to hard disc. All actions will be done, except the
       saving to hard disc. All other options are ignored if this one
       is active. Press 's' to activate this option.

  »» Destination: Enter a different restore directory if your don't want
       to save the files to their original location from where you saved
       them. Very useful if you really test your backup floppies. Make
       sure you have the required amount of free space on your hard disc.
       This option will be activated automatically if you enter a legal
       directory name.

  »» Overwrite existing files: You can choose between 'Overwrite', 'Ask'
       and 'Skip'. With 'Overwrite' all files will be saved, also if the
       file already exists. With 'Ask' a requester appears and asks you
       if you want to overwrite the file. And 'Skip' skips existing files.
       Press the 'o' key to change this settings.

  »» Okay/Cancel: Hmmm, well, click 'Okay' or the <Return> key to start,
       or click 'Cancel' or the <ESC> key to abort.

   @{HI "File Restore Dialog"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  Mainly the same as the backup dialog. At the top you see the history
  list, in the middle the current action and at the bottom two progress
  panels, one for the amount of bytes loaded and one for the number of
  files restored.
  IMPORTANT: You can't abort restoring your files now. And you must use
  your internal floppy drive "DF0:"

   @{HI "Final Restore Report"}
  @{HI "~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~"}
  The same like the backup report. Some statistics about the restore.
  Click 'Save' if you want to save the history list. Else click 'Okay'
  to return to the main menu.

@endnode
@node QUIT "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» Quit"
@prev MAINMENU

  You'll guess want this option does? Right, it quits the program.

@endnode
@node REDIRECT "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» Backup »» Redirect"
@prev BACKUP

  I added this feature because I hate to sit in front of my AMIGA and
  wait while the program is working, just to change the floppy discs.

  Add to the name of your backup add ">>" followed by a directory where
  you want to write the data to. For each floppy a directory with the
  floppies' name will be created. After the backup copy each directory
  on a floppy disc and relabel it to the name of that directory.

  Here is an example:
    As label you typed: "MyBackup>>Dh2:Empty". Then the program
    creates let's say 4 directories, "Dh2:Empty/MyBackup_#0001" to
    "Dh2:Empty/MyBackup_#0004". After the backup you take 4 floppies
    rename the first one to "MyBackup_#0001" and copy the content of
    the directory "Dh2:Empty/MyBackup_#0001" to it. Repeat this for
    the other three directories. That's it.

  You can make the first disc bootable and copy the

@endnode
@node COMPRESSION "Power Backup 1.01 »» Main Menu »» Backup »» Compression"
@prev BACKUP

  If you have the "powerpacker.library" in your LIBS: folder you can
  compress your files. There are six possible types:

  »» @{b}None@{ub}: No compression at all. The only type where the estimation
       is correct. Because of additional informations add one floppy
       and you are on the safe side.

  »» @{b}Fast@{ub}: Not very good, but fast! I would never use it. The estimation
       for this option is about 60% of the original size.

  »» @{b}Normal@{ub}: Little bit better, but not not really good. The estimation
       is about 54% of the original size.

  »» @{b}Good@{ub}: Normal compression. I would start my decision here with an
       estimation of about 50% of the original size.

  »» @{b}Better@{ub}: If you some more minutes, use this type. The estimation is
       about 48% of the original size.

  »» @{b}Best@{ub}: Maximum compression, but it doesn't mid if you redirect the
       backup to hard disc. The estimation is 46% of the original size.

  All estimations are calculated from a mixture of executables, data
  files and text files. If you backup samples or already compressed data
  you need about 80% of the original size! If you have a lot of text files
  or uncompressed data you may only need 40% of the original size. Only
  the final report will show how good/bad your files could be compressed.

@endnode
